{"cursor":"9077","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"]] 'Bonnet' is a term for a wide variety of styles of headgear for both sexes,\nbut most often female, which has been in use from the Middle Ages to the\npresent. It is impossible to generalize as to the styles for which the word has\nbeen used, any more than for the alternatives of hat or cap, but there is for\nboth sexes a tendency to use the word for styles in soft material and lacking a\nbrim. However the term has also been used, for example, for steel helmets. This\nwas from Scotland (in 1505), where the term has long been especially\npopular. OED, \"Bonnet\" Bonnet derives from the same\nword in French, where it originally indicated a type of material. In the 21st\ncentury, only a few kinds of headgear are still referred to as bonnets, most\ncommonly those worn by babies and Scottish soldiers.\n","linknr":376,"url":"Bonnet_(headgear)","recorded":1362566639,"links":36,"instances":["cap","pepper"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Bonnets|","Children's clothing","Headgear","English clothing"],"headings":["Babies","Women","Men","Modern French","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Old_woman_in_sunbonnet_by_Doris_Ulmann.jpg/220px-Old_woman_in_sunbonnet_by_Doris_Ulmann.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/80/Small_child_in_bonnet_and_kyse.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/PompadourDrouais.jpg/250px-PompadourDrouais.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8a/Lebr010.jpg/250px-Lebr010.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ea/Invisibles-Tete-a-Tete-poke-bonnet-satire-1810s.jpg/350px-Invis